1 Question 1

Plot the data and comment on its features. What can you observe? To what political , economical or social event/s it can be linked?

Russia’s annual population had a long period of positive, steady growth from 1960 to the early 1990s. The Russian Federation was facing a significant challenge of elevated mortality rates from non-natural causes, with a majority of such incidents linked to alcoholism [1]. The decline in life expectancy, especially for men in the working-age bracket, had been drastic [1]. In addition, the fertility rate in Russia has dwindled to one of the lowest globally, while simultaneously exhibiting the highest abortion rate [1]. Although this news seems to put a negative effect on the country’s population, the number of birth rates were high, and net positive migration proved to help the upward population trend [2]. There were two migration stages that occurred in the beginning of the 1950s to the mid-1970s [3]. Within this first phase, “Russia lost 2.7 million people to other Soviet republics,” but this turned around in the second stage. Between 1975 and 1991, Russia’s population increased by 2.5 million, which gave those entering the country an opportunity to benefit from state offers [3]. In addition, students played an important role in the population growth since tens of thousands came to study at Russian universities [3]. These are some of the reasons that the trend continued to grow positively throughout those three decades. In 1991, there was a drastic shift, the Soviet Union collapsed. This resulted in a swift change in the trend to be negatively impacted by the economic instability. Daniel Shapiro and Natasha Yefimova-Trilling mentioned how Russia witnessed a steady decline in birth rates coupled with a sharp increase in mortality rates, leading to a relatively smaller cohort of individuals born during this period in comparison to preceding generations. Furthermore, these individuals were currently reaching their optimal childbearing age, resulting in a secondary demographic decline [4]. In the early 1990s, Russia implemented compulsory medical insurance for its citizens, alongside the adoption of fundamental regulatory documents, which would later lead to less deaths [5]. Around 2008, Russia began experiencing a positive trend again in their population growth. This was due to the massive international migration into the country, which by 2017 “was the fourth largest in the world” [4]. Throughout this series, there appears to be no seasonality or cycle.

2 Question 2

Fit a linear trend model and compare this to a piecewise linear trend model with knots at 1993 and 2008.

According to section 7.1, the regression model allows for a linear relationship between the forecast variable \(y\) and a single predictor variable \(x\): \[y_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \epsilon_t\] The coefficients \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) denote the intercept and the slope of the line respectively. The intercept, \(\beta_0\) represents the predicted value of \(y\) when \(x\) = 0. The slope \(\beta_1\) represents the average predicted change in \(y\) resulting from a one unit increase in \(x\).

The fitted line has is an upward slope, insinuating a positive relationship between \(Population\) and \(Year\). The model has a multiple R-squared of 64.12%, explaining roughly 64% of the variance within the population series which seems to be a reasonably good fit.

There are two main assumptions that need to be fulfilled when using a linear regression model. First, we are assuming that the model is a reasonable approximation to reality. This means that the relationship between the forecast variable and the predictor variables satisfies this linear equation (Section 7.1). The second assumption is in relation to the errors. The residuals should have a mean around zero, they are not autocorrelated, and they are unrelated to the predictor variables. Below shows several plots of the residuals.

Unfortunately, the residuals look terrible and these assumptions are not met. But, there is another solution!

Section 7.7: Non-Linear Regression
There are cases for which simply transforming the data will not be adequate and a more general specification may be required. Then the model we use is \[y = f(x) + \epsilon\] where \(f\) is a nonlinear function. In standard (linear) regression, \(f(x) = \beta_0 + \beta_1x\). In the specification of nonlinear regression that follows, we allow \(f\) to be a more flexible nonlinear function of \(x\), compared to simply a logarithmic or other transformation.

One of the simplest specifications is to make \(f\) piecewise linear. That is, we introduce points where the slope of \(f\) can change. These points are called knots. This can be achieved by letting \(x_1 = x\) and introducing variable \(x_2\) such that \[x_2 = (x - c)_+ =\begin{cases} 0 & if\left(x\right) < c \\ x - c & if\left(x\right) \geq c \end{cases}\]

The notation \((x - c)_+\) means the value \(x - c\) if it is positive and 0 otherwise. This forces the slope to bend at point \(c\).

Resource: Forecasting: Principles and Practice (3rd ed) [6]

## [1] 1

There is a story depicted within this series as there are steeper increases in population to those that are more steady. During the mid-20th century, Spain experienced a substantial surge in population growth, facilitated by the baby boom that followed World War II, along with improvements in medical technology and increased life expectancy, which were also observed in other Western European countries [7]. However, from the 1980s, Spain underwent a demographic transition marked by a steep decline in the country’s fertility rate [7]. This resulted in a relatively modest population growth of two million between the mid-1980s and 2000, compared to the previous pace of two million every five to six years [7]. Notably, the population saw a sharp upswing from 2000 to 2008, buoyed by robust economic growth and a substantial influx of immigrants [7]. However, this growth trajectory was curtailed due to the impact of the Great Recession on the Spanish economy [7]. As of 2020, Spain’s population is estimated to be approximately 46.8 million, which places it as the sixth-largest country in Europe, which can be forecasted later [7]. There appears to be no seasonality or cycle.

Resource: https://www.statista.com/statistics/1067088/population-spain-historical [7]

Out of the four forecasts for Russia and Spain, this fit appears to be the most drastic because the model underfits and overfits much more than it previously has for each scenario. Since there is no data past 2017, Statista provided information for the three years after and it appears to be continuously increasing as the forecast predicts [7]. In addition, the predicted values are overfitted or underfitted depending on the year. In the beginning and end, it seems that the model underfits while the middle of this time period is overfitted. At the end of the time series, the population appears to grow again but the trend is not long enough to conclude that this forecast should be directed upward compared to how it is facing downward.
